  "prompt": "If a truck is hauling 1000 pounds of parakeets that are all sitting on their perch does it get 1000 pounds lighter if they all fly at the same time?",
  "response": "No, the truck does not become 1000 pounds lighter if all the parakeets fly at the same time. While the parakeets are in the air, they are still exerting their weight downwards onto the truck through the air. This is due to the principle of conservation of momentum and how forces work.\n\nWhen the parakeets are perched, their weight is directly transferred to the truck. When they fly, they push down on the air with their wings, and the air in turn pushes back up. This exertion of force keeps the total weight that the truck supports the same. Thus, the truck's weight remains essentially unchanged regardless of whether the parakeets are sitting or flying. \n\nIn summary, the truck\u2019s weight remains the same while the parakeets are flying; the truck does not become lighter.",
